## Part 1: Go Language Fundamentals (2.5 hours)

### Theory: What is Go?

Go is a compiled, statically-typed language designed for simplicity and performance:

| Aspect | Go |
|--------|-----|
| **Syntax** | Simple, readable (inspired by C) |
| **Typing** | Static + inference |
| **Memory** | Garbage collected |
| **Concurrency** | Built-in with goroutines |
| **Compilation** | Single binary, no runtime needed |
| **Error Handling** | Explicit (no exceptions) |

**Comparison to other languages:**

| Coming from... | Go feels like... |
|---|---|
| Java | Like Java without the verbosity |
| Python | Like Python but compiled and faster |
| JavaScript | Like JavaScript with static types |
| C | Much simpler but with GC |

### Mandatory Reading

- [Go Documentation - Getting Started](https://go.dev/doc/tutorial/getting-started) (15 min)
- [Effective Go](https://go.dev/doc/effective_go) - Read sections on Formatting through Interfaces (30 min)

