### 1.1 Variables and Types

```go
package main

import "fmt"

func main() {
    // Type inference with :=
    name := "John"           // Inferred as string
    age := 30                // Inferred as int
    salary := 50000.50       // Inferred as float64
    isActive := true         // Inferred as bool

    // Explicit type declaration
    var firstName string = "Jane"
    var count int = 42
    var price float64 = 19.99

    // Short variable declaration (inside functions only)
    id := "user123"

    // Const - compile-time constant
    const maxRetries = 3
    const apiVersion = "1.0"

    // Blank identifier - ignore unused variables
    _, err := someFunction()

    fmt.Println(name, age, salary, isActive)
}

func someFunction() (string, error) {
    return "result", nil
}
```

**Key Differences from Other Languages:**

| Feature | Go | Java | Python | JS |
|---------|-----|------|--------|-----|
| Type inference | `:= "hello"` | Not standard | `x = "hello"` | `let x = "hello"` |
| Declaration | `var x string` | `String x;` | `x = ""` | `var x = ""` |
| Multiple return | `return x, err` | No | No | No |
| Zero values | `var x int` → 0 | Not really | No | undefined |

### 1.2 Strings and String Operations

```go
package main

import (
    "fmt"
    "strings"
)

func main() {
    // String literals
    name := "Alice"
    greeting := "Hello, " + name  // Concatenation with +

    // String interpolation using fmt
    message := fmt.Sprintf("Hello, %s", name)
    message = fmt.Sprintf("Name: %s, Age: %d", name, 30)

    // Useful string operations
    text := "  Hello World  "
    fmt.Println(strings.TrimSpace(text))      // "Hello World"
    fmt.Println(strings.ToUpper(text))        // "  HELLO WORLD  "
    fmt.Println(strings.Contains(text, "World")) // true
    fmt.Println(strings.Split("a,b,c", ","))  // [a b c]
    fmt.Println(strings.Join([]string{"a", "b"}, ",")) // "a,b"

    // Rune (Unicode character)
    char := 'A'
    fmt.Println(char)  // 65 (ASCII value)

    // Byte slice from string
    bytes := []byte(text)
    fmt.Println(bytes)
}
```

