## Part 3: Interfaces and Abstraction (1.5 hours)

### 3.1 Interfaces

```go
package main

import (
    "fmt"
    "io"
)

// Define an interface (contract)
type Writer interface {
    Write(p []byte) (n int, err error)
}

type Logger interface {
    Info(msg string)
    Error(msg string)
}

// Concrete implementation 1
type ConsoleLogger struct{}

func (l ConsoleLogger) Info(msg string) {
    fmt.Println("INFO:", msg)
}

func (l ConsoleLogger) Error(msg string) {
    fmt.Println("ERROR:", msg)
}

// Concrete implementation 2
type SilentLogger struct{}

func (l SilentLogger) Info(msg string)  {}
func (l SilentLogger) Error(msg string) {}

// Function that accepts any Logger
func DoWork(logger Logger) {
    logger.Info("Starting work")
    logger.Error("Encountered error")
    logger.Info("Work done")
}

func main() {
    console := ConsoleLogger{}
    silent := SilentLogger{}

    DoWork(console)  // Prints messages
    DoWork(silent)   // Silent

    // Go's interface satisfaction is implicit
    // No need to declare "implements"
}
```

**Key Insight:** In Go, you don't declare that a type implements an interface. If it has all the required methods, it automatically implements it. This is called **structural subtyping**.

### 3.2 Embedding (Composition over Inheritance)

```go
package main

import "fmt"

type Animal struct {
    Name string
}

func (a Animal) Speak() string {
    return fmt.Sprintf("%s makes a sound", a.Name)
}

// Dog embeds Animal - inherits its fields and methods
type Dog struct {
    Animal  // Embedded type
    Breed   string
}

// Override the Speak method
func (d Dog) Speak() string {
    return fmt.Sprintf("%s barks", d.Name)
}

func main() {
    dog := Dog{
        Animal: Animal{Name: "Buddy"},
        Breed:  "Golden Retriever",
    }

    fmt.Println(dog.Speak())  // Buddy barks
    fmt.Println(dog.Name)     // Buddy (inherited from Animal)
}
```

