## Part 4: Packages and Organization (1 hour)

### 4.1 Package Structure

In Go, organization happens at the **package** level:

```
myproject/
├── main.go              # package main (executable)
├── go.mod              # Module definition
├── go.sum              # Dependency checksums
├── internal/
│   ├── user/
│   │   ├── user.go     # package user
│   │   └── user_test.go
│   └── auth/
│       └── auth.go      # package auth
└── pkg/
    └── logger/
        └── logger.go    # package logger
```

### 4.2 Importing and Exporting

```go
// user.go in internal/user package
package user

// Exported (capital letter) - can be imported
type User struct {
    ID   string
    Name string
}

// Exported function
func (u User) GetDisplayName() string {
    return u.Name
}

// Unexported (lowercase) - private to package
func validateEmail(email string) bool {
    return true
}

---

// main.go
package main

import (
    "fmt"
    "myproject/internal/user"
)

func main() {
    u := user.User{ID: "1", Name: "John"}
    fmt.Println(u.GetDisplayName())

    // This would fail:
    // user.validateEmail("test@test.com")  // Error: validateEmail not exported
}
```

### 4.3 Project Structure in Ellume Core

```
ellume-core/
├── cmd/server/           # main.go lives here
├── pkg/                  # Importable packages
│   ├── config/          # Configuration handling
│   ├── logger/          # Logger abstraction
│   ├── middleware/      # HTTP middleware
│   ├── provider/        # Database & auth providers
│   └── authorization/   # Authorization utilities
├── module/              # Business logic (layered)
│   ├── user/
│   │   ├── dl.go       # Data Layer
│   │   ├── bl.go       # Business Logic
│   │   └── handler.go  # HTTP handlers
│   └── auth/
└── database/            # Migrations and schema
```

**Important:**
- `pkg/` contains reusable, importable packages
- `module/` contains business logic organized by feature
- `internal/` would be used for app-specific code not meant for reuse

